00:20:14.300 --> 00:20:17.300
And Etsy had this kind of amazing DevOps team.

00:20:17.300 --> 00:20:19.300
And so, for those of you who don't know,

00:20:19.300 --> 00:20:22.300
DevOps stands for developer operator.

00:20:22.300 --> 00:20:25.300
And it's this field where, essentially,

00:20:25.300 --> 00:20:28.300
it was, like, kind of taking IT to the next level.

00:20:28.300 --> 00:20:30.300
So it was saying the people who run the website,

00:20:30.300 --> 00:20:32.300
the people who keep the servers on for the website,

00:20:32.300 --> 00:20:35.300
the people who do everything to kind of keep this,

00:20:35.300 --> 00:20:37.300
you know, shopping website up,

00:20:37.300 --> 00:20:40.300
they should also be the people developing the tools

00:20:40.300 --> 00:20:42.300
to keep the website up.

00:20:42.300 --> 00:20:44.300
And so it's, like, developer operator.

00:20:44.300 --> 00:20:48.300
And at Google, they kind of have a different word for it,

00:20:48.300 --> 00:20:51.300
site reliability engineer, but it's the same thing.

00:20:51.300 --> 00:20:55.300
And I was really inspired by that work

00:20:55.300 --> 00:20:57.300
and kind of how they approach problems.

00:20:57.300 --> 00:20:59.300
One of the central tenets was this idea

00:20:59.300 --> 00:21:01.300
of a blameless postmortem,

00:21:01.300 --> 00:21:03.300
where if you ran into a problem,

00:21:03.300 --> 00:21:05.300
like, let's say your system failed

00:21:05.300 --> 00:21:07.300
and the website went down,

00:21:07.300 --> 00:21:11.300
there is a human tendency to, like, blame the person

00:21:11.300 --> 00:21:13.300
who wrote the code that failed or whatever.

00:21:13.300 --> 00:21:16.300
But Etsy focused a lot on, instead,

00:21:16.300 --> 00:21:18.300
doing this thing called a blameless postmortem,

00:21:18.300 --> 00:21:23.300
where you talk about, like, you frame the problem

00:21:23.300 --> 00:21:25.300
as though the system failed the operator

00:21:25.300 --> 00:21:28.300
rather than the operator failing within a good system.

00:21:28.300 --> 00:21:30.300
And then that opens up the conversation

00:21:30.300 --> 00:21:33.300
to, like, talk about iterating on the system

00:21:33.300 --> 00:21:34.300
and saying, you know, okay,

00:21:34.300 --> 00:21:36.300
this person went to work this day,

00:21:36.300 --> 00:21:38.300
said they wanted to do a good job.

00:21:38.300 --> 00:21:40.300
They did not say they wanted to take down the website.

00:21:40.300 --> 00:21:42.300
But then the system, like,

00:21:42.300 --> 00:21:44.300
allowed them to take down the website.

00:21:44.300 --> 00:21:48.300
And so, like, based on this kind of idea

00:21:48.300 --> 00:21:49.300
of, like, how do we know what to do,

00:21:49.300 --> 00:21:51.300
there were sort of these two threads that started.

00:21:51.300 --> 00:21:54.300
One was how do we decide, like,

00:21:54.300 --> 00:21:56.300
how to build the artifact,

00:21:56.300 --> 00:22:00.300
like the dashboard or the email or the report, whatever.

00:22:00.300 --> 00:22:02.300
And then there was this kind of, like,

00:22:02.300 --> 00:22:03.300
how do you build a narrative?

00:22:03.300 --> 00:22:05.300
And so I think, like,

00:22:05.300 --> 00:22:07.300
the theme of the early part of the podcast,

00:22:07.300 --> 00:22:08.300
really for the first year,

00:22:08.300 --> 00:22:11.300
