00:42:27.300 --> 00:42:29.300
It's amazing how just a simple

00:42:29.300 --> 00:42:31.300
kind of formulation of a problem

00:42:31.300 --> 00:42:33.300
can bring in every single aspect

00:42:33.300 --> 00:42:35.300
of design, of

00:42:35.300 --> 00:42:37.300
analysis, you know, presentation, communication.

00:42:37.300 --> 00:42:39.300
Yeah, exactly.

00:42:39.300 --> 00:42:41.300
Like, you're doing the whole thing.

00:42:41.300 --> 00:42:43.300
And what I like about it, too, is that

00:42:43.300 --> 00:42:45.300
the things like how you store the

00:42:45.300 --> 00:42:47.300
data is sort of on the same

00:42:47.300 --> 00:42:49.300
par as, like,

00:42:49.300 --> 00:42:51.300
what models you choose. Like, all of

00:42:51.300 --> 00:42:53.300
those things are equal. You have to end up spending time

00:42:53.300 --> 00:42:55.300
on all of it instead of

00:42:55.300 --> 00:42:57.300
I feel like as a

00:42:57.300 --> 00:42:59.300
field, and what I like about this conference

00:42:59.300 --> 00:43:01.300
is that, less so here, but as a field

00:43:01.300 --> 00:43:03.300
we focus so much just on the methods, and that

00:43:03.300 --> 00:43:05.300
really bothers me, in case

00:43:05.300 --> 00:43:07.300
that hasn't been clear.

00:43:07.300 --> 00:43:09.300
And I was actually

00:43:09.300 --> 00:43:11.300
talking with someone last night about that, where I'm like, you know,

00:43:11.300 --> 00:43:13.300
in some ways

00:43:13.300 --> 00:43:15.300
like, the way that

00:43:15.300 --> 00:43:17.300
normal data science conferences

00:43:17.300 --> 00:43:19.300
are structured,

00:43:19.300 --> 00:43:21.300
it's like, everyone wants to talk about

00:43:21.300 --> 00:43:23.300
the best method, like the latest

00:43:23.300 --> 00:43:25.300
thing. And literally, in that

00:43:25.300 --> 00:43:27.300
system, you're motivated to have bad

00:43:27.300 --> 00:43:29.300
data, because it gives you

00:43:29.300 --> 00:43:31.300
more opportunity to do fancier

00:43:31.300 --> 00:43:33.300
models. And so, like,

00:43:33.300 --> 00:43:35.300
any system where it's like, oh, okay,

00:43:35.300 --> 00:43:37.300
this person could work on worse

00:43:37.300 --> 00:43:39.300
and worse data and be equally

00:43:39.300 --> 00:43:41.300
happy because they get to do all these fancy

00:43:41.300 --> 00:43:43.300
things they learned at this conference,

00:43:43.300 --> 00:43:45.300
is like, that's not solving the

00:43:45.300 --> 00:43:47.300
problem. That's like

00:43:47.300 --> 00:43:49.300
choosing not to solve the problem.

00:43:49.300 --> 00:43:51.300
So by focusing on the whole thing, it's like, no, okay,

00:43:51.300 --> 00:43:53.300
can you hone in on exactly what data

00:43:53.300 --> 00:43:55.300
you need, rather than just

00:43:55.300 --> 00:43:57.300
making do with what might

00:43:57.300 --> 00:43:59.300
have fallen into your lap

00:43:59.300 --> 00:44:01.300
somewhere. I think one of the hardest things to do

00:44:01.300 --> 00:44:03.300
in general, but also

00:44:03.300 --> 00:44:05.300
in data science, is to kind of

00:44:05.300 --> 00:44:07.300
pull

00:44:07.300 --> 00:44:09.300
back from trying to maximize in a single

00:44:09.300 --> 00:44:11.300
dimension. And I think,

00:44:11.300 --> 00:44:13.300
to me, the way I interpreted

00:44:13.300 --> 00:44:15.300
even JJ's talk, is like,

00:44:15.300 --> 00:44:17.300
the way that corporations

00:44:17.300 --> 00:44:19.300
are structured is they maximize on a certain

00:44:19.300 --> 00:44:21.300
one dimension. And I think

00:44:21.300 --> 00:44:23.300
it's hard, that can

00:44:23.300 --> 00:44:25.300
end up with some good and some bad.

00:44:25.300 --> 00:44:27.300
And I think in data science, it's very tempting

00:44:27.300 --> 00:44:29.300
to kind of go for the optimal approach, go for the optimal

00:44:29.300 --> 00:44:31.300
method, go for the best

00:44:31.300 --> 00:44:33.300
prediction. But there are other elements

00:44:33.300 --> 00:44:35.300
as other stakeholders, there are other trade-offs

00:44:35.300 --> 00:44:37.300
to be made. I really like that

00:44:37.300 --> 00:44:39.300
because in the second talk,

00:44:39.300 --> 00:44:41.300
she just

00:44:41.300 --> 00:44:43.300
touched it briefly at the end,

00:44:43.300 --> 00:44:45.300
but it was like, what are

00:44:45.300 --> 00:44:47.300
UX problems and what are

00:44:47.300 --> 00:44:49.300
designer problems? And then

00:44:49.300 --> 00:44:51.300
the one that was like, this is actually a design

00:44:51.300 --> 00:44:53.300
problem, was the loss function.

00:44:53.300 --> 00:44:55.300
It seems like it's just a data science problem,

00:44:55.300 --> 00:44:57.300
but that's actually the core

00:44:57.300 --> 00:44:59.300
user experience, is what loss function you use.

00:44:59.300 --> 00:45:01.300
And what system are you actually building?

00:45:01.300 --> 00:45:03.300
And what I like about that is that

00:45:03.300 --> 00:45:05.300
it's like the same with the corporation thing.

00:45:05.300 --> 00:45:07.300
It's like, what was the loss function

00:45:07.300 --> 00:45:09.300
before versus that?

00:45:09.300 --> 00:45:11.300
Change the KPIs, basically.

00:45:11.300 --> 00:45:13.300
KPI, key performance

00:45:13.300 --> 00:45:15.300
indicator. I don't deal with KPIs.

00:45:15.300 --> 00:45:17.300
What? I don't deal with KPIs. Yeah, you don't

00:45:17.300 --> 00:45:19.300
deal with KPIs. Not yet, at least.

00:45:19.300 --> 00:45:21.300
Yeah, the way I've been talking about that

00:45:21.300 --> 00:45:23.300
at Stitch Fix is like, yeah, how do we

00:45:23.300 --> 00:45:25.300
rather than just

00:45:25.300 --> 00:45:27.300
optimizing for sales, how can we

00:45:27.300 --> 00:45:29.300
construct new KPIs that might

00:45:29.300 --> 00:45:31.300
lead to different user experiences?

00:45:31.300 --> 00:45:33.300
I feel like it would be great if we could move to a place

00:45:33.300 --> 00:45:35.300
where instead of saying, this is the best thing,

00:45:35.300 --> 00:45:37.300
we could say,

00:45:37.300 --> 00:45:39.300
I really appreciate this set of trade-offs.

00:45:39.300 --> 00:45:41.300
Yeah, yeah.

00:45:41.300 --> 00:45:43.300
I like that. I don't know, but it doesn't quite

00:45:43.300 --> 00:45:45.300
sound as nice,

00:45:45.300 --> 00:45:47.300
I guess. I don't know.

00:45:47.300 --> 00:45:49.300
I think it sounds...

00:45:49.300 --> 00:45:51.300
I have one person with me here.

00:45:51.300 --> 00:45:53.300
One other thing

00:45:53.300 --> 00:45:55.300
that, kind of like the end of this timeline,

00:45:55.300 --> 00:45:57.300
this has just been briefly,

00:45:57.300 --> 00:45:59.300
but essentially

00:45:59.300 --> 00:46:01.300
by getting to this place, now it opens up

00:46:01.300 --> 00:46:03.300
a whole other set of

00:46:03.300 --> 00:46:05.300
fields to look into,

00:46:05.300 --> 00:46:07.300
which is everything around

00:46:07.300 --> 00:46:09.300
creativity.

00:46:09.300 --> 00:46:11.300
The book I'm mentioning,

00:46:11.300 --> 00:46:13.300
that we're mentioning here, is called The Creative Curve,

00:46:13.300 --> 00:46:15.300
and we had a one-episode

00:46:15.300 --> 00:46:17.300
book club on that.

00:46:17.300 --> 00:46:19.300
Learn our lesson.

00:46:19.300 --> 00:46:21.300
Yeah.

00:46:21.300 --> 00:46:23.300
I was actually about to suggest that we should do more.

00:46:23.300 --> 00:46:25.300
I was like, let's retroactively go back

00:46:25.300 --> 00:46:27.300
and do three episodes on that one.

00:46:27.300 --> 00:46:29.300
Anyway.

00:46:29.300 --> 00:46:31.300
The idea with that was that it was someone,

00:46:31.300 --> 00:46:33.300
this guy, Alan Gannett, who essentially

00:46:33.300 --> 00:46:35.300
empirically studied creative people

00:46:35.300 --> 00:46:37.300
and how

00:46:37.300 --> 00:46:39.300
they operate.

00:46:39.300 --> 00:46:41.300
I thought it was awesome.

00:46:41.300 --> 00:46:43.300
I really liked it. It really made me feel like,

00:46:43.300 --> 00:46:45.300
oh, I can apply these principles to my data science work.

00:46:45.300 --> 00:46:47.300
The principles

00:46:47.300 --> 00:46:49.300
were...

00:46:49.300 --> 00:46:51.300
I don't think I did ever

00:46:51.300 --> 00:46:53.300
write them down. Consumption. Yeah.

00:46:53.300 --> 00:46:55.300
There was consumption.

00:46:55.300 --> 00:46:57.300
Creative people will frequently...

00:46:57.300 --> 00:46:59.300
People who...

00:46:59.300 --> 00:47:01.300
This is why I'm confused with you.

00:47:01.300 --> 00:47:03.300
People who are engaged in movie making,

00:47:03.300 --> 00:47:05.300
they watch movies 20%

00:47:05.300 --> 00:47:07.300
of the time.

00:47:07.300 --> 00:47:09.300
You're not like that for whatever reason.

00:47:09.300 --> 00:47:11.300
That's a different story.

00:47:11.300 --> 00:47:13.300
You look at...

00:47:13.300 --> 00:47:15.300
Just again, from empirically looking at people

00:47:15.300 --> 00:47:17.300
in these creative fields,

00:47:17.300 --> 00:47:19.300
consuming other people's work is a big part of it.

00:47:19.300 --> 00:47:21.300
You digest it, you think about it,

00:47:21.300 --> 00:47:23.300
and you iterate on it.

00:47:23.300 --> 00:47:25.300
I think that aspect...

00:47:25.300 --> 00:47:27.300
If you want to write, you read a lot of books.

00:47:27.300 --> 00:47:29.300
If you want to write music,

00:47:29.300 --> 00:47:31.300
you listen to a lot of music.

00:47:31.300 --> 00:47:33.300
One of the aspects that's difficult about data analysis

00:47:33.300 --> 00:47:35.300
is it's not always easy to read a lot of data analyses

00:47:35.300 --> 00:47:37.300
because they're not out there.

00:47:37.300 --> 00:47:39.300
Especially in the corporate world,

00:47:39.300 --> 00:47:41.300
data science specifically.

00:47:41.300 --> 00:47:43.300
If you have a big team, you can read

00:47:43.300 --> 00:47:45.300
whatever other people are doing,

00:47:45.300 --> 00:47:47.300
but otherwise, basically only at conferences.

00:47:47.300 --> 00:47:49.300
Or David Robinson's livestream.

00:47:49.300 --> 00:47:51.300
Yeah.

00:47:51.300 --> 00:47:53.300
It's hard to consume a lot of data analysis

00:47:53.300 --> 00:47:55.300
is what I think it comes down to.

00:47:55.300 --> 00:47:57.300
I think that's a key step to becoming

00:47:57.300 --> 00:47:59.300
an expert in something.

00:47:59.300 --> 00:48:01.300
That's a great point.

00:48:01.300 --> 00:48:03.300
Iteration.

00:48:03.300 --> 00:48:05.300
Is there imitation too?

00:48:05.300 --> 00:48:07.300
Iteration.

00:48:07.300 --> 00:48:09.300
Iteration is this idea that you just

00:48:09.300 --> 00:48:11.300
keep going.

00:48:11.300 --> 00:48:13.300
You keep doing things.

00:48:13.300 --> 00:48:15.300
You do it over and over.

00:48:15.300 --> 00:48:17.300
Again, that is touched in the design literature too.

00:48:17.300 --> 00:48:19.300
You've got to keep doing things.

00:48:19.300 --> 00:48:21.300
Ideas are going to evolve over time.

00:48:21.300 --> 00:48:23.300
Part of why we wanted to go through those clips

00:48:23.300 --> 00:48:25.300
and put up this timeline

00:48:25.300 --> 00:48:27.300
is that

00:48:27.300 --> 00:48:29.300
even the creativity

00:48:29.300 --> 00:48:31.300
that we got from this podcast

00:48:31.300 --> 00:48:33.300
that I totally wasn't expecting.

00:48:33.300 --> 00:48:35.300
It took us four years.

00:48:35.300 --> 00:48:37.300
This timeline is over four years.

00:48:37.300 --> 00:48:39.300
Timeline's not to scale.

00:48:39.300 --> 00:48:41.300
Yeah, definitely not to scale.

00:48:41.300 --> 00:48:43.300
The number of ways that we attacked this problem

00:48:43.300 --> 00:48:45.300
and thought about it

00:48:45.300 --> 00:48:47.300
was a lot.

00:48:47.300 --> 00:48:49.300
It never felt like it was work necessarily.

00:48:49.300 --> 00:48:51.300
It was just iterating

00:48:51.300 --> 00:48:53.300
and going on.

00:48:53.300 --> 00:48:55.300
Then there's the community.

00:48:55.300 --> 00:48:57.300
Yeah.

00:48:57.300 --> 00:48:59.300
The community one.

00:48:59.300 --> 00:49:01.300
Another one is creative communities.

00:49:01.300 --> 00:49:03.300
You look at artists.

00:49:03.300 --> 00:49:05.300
Andy Warhol had the factory

00:49:05.300 --> 00:49:07.300
where it was just a bunch of artists

00:49:07.300 --> 00:49:09.300
in a loft

00:49:09.300 --> 00:49:11.300
painting, giving feedback.

00:49:11.300 --> 00:49:13.300
With that,

00:49:13.300 --> 00:49:15.300
surrounding yourself with other creative people

00:49:15.300 --> 00:49:17.300
helps you be creative.

00:49:17.300 --> 00:49:19.300
That's kind of like

00:49:19.300 --> 00:49:21.300
my sitcom

00:49:21.300 --> 00:49:23.300
happy ending here.

00:49:23.300 --> 00:49:25.300
Coming to conferences like this,

00:49:25.300 --> 00:49:27.300
they're fun, they're energizing.

00:49:27.300 --> 00:49:29.300
I do think

00:49:29.300 --> 00:49:31.300
they embody this creative community.

00:49:31.300 --> 00:49:33.300
Especially because so many people

00:49:33.300 --> 00:49:35.300
are isolated as data scientists.

00:49:35.300 --> 00:49:37.300
Not every company

00:49:37.300 --> 00:49:39.300
has 100 data scientists.

00:49:39.300 --> 00:49:41.300
Most companies don't.

00:49:41.300 --> 00:49:43.300
Being able to get together

00:49:43.300 --> 00:49:45.300
and bounce ideas off

00:49:45.300 --> 00:49:47.300
and see what other people are doing.

00:49:47.300 --> 00:49:49.300
I guess what I'm trying to say is

00:49:49.300 --> 00:49:51.300
that is the work.

00:49:51.300 --> 00:49:53.300
It's not like this isn't

00:49:53.300 --> 00:49:55.300
productive, if that makes sense.

00:49:55.300 --> 00:49:57.300
There was one agenda item

00:49:57.300 --> 00:49:59.300
for starting the podcast.

00:49:59.300 --> 00:50:01.300
Part of it was to

00:50:01.300 --> 00:50:03.300
produce that community

00:50:03.300 --> 00:50:05.300
of people who may be sitting

00:50:05.300 --> 00:50:07.300
in a department somewhere or

00:50:07.300 --> 00:50:09.300
in a company somewhere by themselves.

00:50:09.300 --> 00:50:11.300
They're forced to be the lone data analyst.

00:50:11.300 --> 00:50:13.300
They don't have anyone to talk to

00:50:13.300 --> 00:50:15.300
or they don't have the ability

00:50:15.300 --> 00:50:17.300
to hear what other people are working on

00:50:17.300 --> 00:50:19.300
and how they're approaching it.

00:50:19.300 --> 00:50:21.300
That's some of the most

00:50:21.300 --> 00:50:23.300
meaningful feedback I hear.

00:50:23.300 --> 00:50:25.300
When people are like,

00:50:25.300 --> 00:50:27.300
I'm alone and it's really nice

00:50:27.300 --> 00:50:29.300
to be able to hear how other people are working.

00:50:29.300 --> 00:50:31.300
That makes me feel really good.

00:50:31.300 --> 00:50:33.300
And then feedback.

00:50:33.300 --> 00:50:35.300
Feedback, yeah.

00:50:35.300 --> 00:50:37.300
Feedback.

00:50:37.300 --> 00:50:39.300
This one is definitely hard.

00:50:39.300 --> 00:50:41.300
A big part of

00:50:41.300 --> 00:50:43.300
in this creative

00:50:43.300 --> 00:50:45.300
curve book and just in general with design

00:50:45.300 --> 00:50:47.300
you actively

00:50:47.300 --> 00:50:49.300
are soliciting user feedback all the time.

00:50:49.300 --> 00:50:51.300
That's a huge part

00:50:51.300 --> 00:50:53.300
of it and you cannot

00:50:53.300 --> 00:50:55.300
be attached

00:50:55.300 --> 00:50:57.300
to what you've produced, essentially.

00:50:57.300 --> 00:50:59.300
You have to let the users tell you what to do.

00:50:59.300 --> 00:51:01.300
I think that that is

00:51:01.300 --> 00:51:03.300
extremely hard.

00:51:03.300 --> 00:51:05.300
Getting feedback is hard.

00:51:05.300 --> 00:51:07.300
Definitely

00:51:07.300 --> 00:51:09.300
not something that people are trained to do.

00:51:13.300 --> 00:51:15.300
Maybe it's just curmudgeonly

00:51:15.300 --> 00:51:17.300
because I see it the most

00:51:17.300 --> 00:51:19.300
but I feel like, especially in

00:51:19.300 --> 00:51:21.300
academic stats and in

00:51:21.300 --> 00:51:23.300
data science in general,

00:51:23.300 --> 00:51:25.300
people do take it really personally.

00:51:25.300 --> 00:51:27.300
There's that quote that I

00:51:27.300 --> 00:51:29.300
kind of hate where it's like,

00:51:29.300 --> 00:51:31.300
photographers and statisticians both

00:51:31.300 --> 00:51:33.300
fall in love with their models.

00:51:37.300 --> 00:51:39.300
I feel bad.

00:51:39.300 --> 00:51:41.300
It makes the point.

00:51:41.300 --> 00:51:43.300
You see people

00:51:43.300 --> 00:51:45.300
really dig their heels in

00:51:45.300 --> 00:51:47.300
and it just gets personal.

00:51:47.300 --> 00:51:49.300
What I like

00:51:49.300 --> 00:51:51.300
is that, at least with the user,

00:51:51.300 --> 00:51:53.300
I think in the design field there's a lot more focus

00:51:53.300 --> 00:51:55.300
on that accepting

00:51:55.300 --> 00:51:57.300
feedback.

00:51:57.300 --> 00:51:59.300
Also, another thing,

00:51:59.300 --> 00:52:01.300
Hilary's personal corner,

00:52:01.300 --> 00:52:03.300
the one thing

00:52:03.300 --> 00:52:05.300
I did not expect

00:52:05.300 --> 00:52:07.300
from starting this kind of meditation

00:52:07.300 --> 00:52:09.300
practice and going down that path is that

00:52:09.300 --> 00:52:11.300
it genuinely

00:52:11.300 --> 00:52:13.300
made me better at getting

00:52:13.300 --> 00:52:15.300
empathy and getting feedback.

00:52:15.300 --> 00:52:17.300
The whole idea is

00:52:17.300 --> 00:52:19.300
dissociating

00:52:19.300 --> 00:52:21.300
yourself from who you think you are.

00:52:21.300 --> 00:52:23.300
It allows you

00:52:23.300 --> 00:52:25.300
to not feel personally threatened

00:52:25.300 --> 00:52:27.300
if someone challenges you.

00:52:27.300 --> 00:52:29.300
People take it personally

00:52:29.300 --> 00:52:31.300
when your whole identity is that

00:52:31.300 --> 00:52:33.300
you're a statistician and you're smart.

00:52:33.300 --> 00:52:35.300
If someone says your

00:52:35.300 --> 00:52:37.300
model is wrong, it's like,

00:52:37.300 --> 00:52:39.300
oh no, I'm not smart anymore. My whole identity

00:52:39.300 --> 00:52:41.300
is gone. Then you're

00:52:41.300 --> 00:52:43.300
defensive.

00:52:43.300 --> 00:52:45.300
Figuring out

00:52:45.300 --> 00:52:47.300
ways, and for me, meditation,

00:52:47.300 --> 00:52:49.300
just figuring out ways to

00:52:49.300 --> 00:52:51.300
detach yourself from that

00:52:51.300 --> 00:52:53.300
makes you able to take feedback.

00:52:53.300 --> 00:52:55.300
Then that actually makes you

00:52:55.300 --> 00:52:57.300
better at the thing. It's kind of like a paradox.

00:52:57.300 --> 00:52:59.300
It's not like a

00:52:59.300 --> 00:53:01.300
magical thing. It's something that can be practiced.

00:53:01.300 --> 00:53:03.300
Exactly. The thing

00:53:03.300 --> 00:53:05.300
about the meditation practice that

00:53:05.300 --> 00:53:07.300
was a big paradigm shift for me was

00:53:07.300 --> 00:53:09.300
that these things aren't just fixed properties.

00:53:09.300 --> 00:53:11.300
It's not just like, oh, this person's

00:53:11.300 --> 00:53:13.300
good at getting feedback or this person has a thick skin

